these advances and early work that called attention to the use of ma- chine learning techniques to detect maritime data anomalies by exam- ining unexpected data patterns using Support Vector Machines (SVM) and neural networks (Obradovic et al., 2014), little work has focused on utilizing advanced analytic techniques such as machine learning or NLP to improve the accuracy and completeness of the critical heterogeneous input data and repositories that are essential to robust and accurate risk analyses. The next section describes a project undertaken for the U.S. Coast Guard that developed such a capability in the context of a mari- time data risk analytics project.
3. The Coast Guard Data Risk Analytics Project
Advances in probabilistic accident modeling and data analytic methods offer the potential to explain and predict accidents and in- cidents with increasing accuracy, using large stores of accessible data and sophisticated analytical tools. In 2017, the U.S. Coast Guard initi- ated a Data Risk Analytics project to develop an architecture, demon- stration analytics, and prototype decision support capability to allow the Coast Guard to better leverage currently available data and analytic methodologies in pursuit of its maritime accident and incident preven- tion mission objectives using the Port of New Orleans as a demonstration focus (Grabowski et al., 2019).
The Coast Guard Data Risk Analytics Project was intended to provide U.S. Coast Guard Headquarters (USCG HQ), Sector New Orleans and District 8 decision makers with risk analytics on the Lower Mississippi River through a daily risk outlook for the 25-mile section of river around Algiers Point (Mississippi River mile markers 85-95). The system pro- vided a visualization of integrated data streams and data analytics, supported by web-based application programming interfaces (APIs). The project architecture provided a data processing framework for collect- ing, cleaning, fusing and validating data from multiple data sources (Table 1); developed an accident-incident database integrating hetero- geneous structured and unstructured text, numerical, image, video and URL data from Table 1 sources; and utilized text mining and machine learning capabilities to analyze the database to provide predictive an- alytics and visualization tools for the Coast Guard’s real-time daily river segment risk assessments.
4. Method
Day to day risk for a particular river mile was characterized by waterway characteristics, transiting vessel characteristics and environ- mental characteristics, the data for which are described in Table 2.
The risk represented by all three types of characteristics was com- bined into a single model that output a risk metric indicative of river segment risk and the potential for dynamic river segment risk, as determined by anticipated vessel traffic and weather conditions for the current day. The daily measure of relative risk per river mile of the Lower Mississippi River around New Orleans shown in Fig. 1 was developed using Probabilistic Risk Assessment, machine learning clas- sification and data mining and Tables 1 and 2 data (Grabowski et al., 2019).
4.1. Risk analysis/modeling
The risk model was developed using multiple machine learning classification techniques to determine the best model fit; techniques included Support Vector Machines (SVM) with kernel functions for non- linear boundaries; the Random Forest (RF) technique; Artificial Neural Networks (ANNs) and Deep Neural Networks (deep-learning). Hierar- chical models were also employed, offering the possibility of better explanation, by considering the probability of an event happening through a single classification model, and then aggregating the events along with the consequences through a probability graphic model or Bayesian Network (Grabowski et al., 2019).
